{{Infobox park | name = Five Canyons Open Space | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = | map = <!-- or | map_image = --> | map_width = | type = Open space | location = Alameda County | nearest_city = Hayward, California | coordinates = {{coord|37.6865|-122.0285|region:US_CA_type:forest|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|300|acres|km2}} | created = 1998 | operator = East Bay Regional Park District | visitation_num = | status = | designation = | open = }}
'''Five Canyons Open Space''' (FCOS) is located in [[Castro Valley, California|Castro Valley]], in [[Alameda County, California]]. Five Canyons is a multi-agency collaboration between East Bay Regional Parks District (EBRPD), Alameda County Public Works, Hayward Area Recreation and Parks District (HARD), and several homeowners associations. EBRPD is the lead agency for this open space. FCOS opened in 1998, consists of {{convert|300|acres|km2}} and {{convert|5|miles|km}} of trails and has almost no amenities. The main visitors are hikers, bicyclists, equestrians and dog walkers. Restrooms and drinking water are available at HARD's nearby Five Canyons Park.<ref name= "EBRPD FCOS Map">[http://www.ebparks.org/Assets/_Nav_Categories/Parks/Maps/Five+Canyons+text.pdf "Five Canyons Open Space and Trail System (Map text)." East Bay Regional Parks District.] Accessed August 24, 2017.</ref>
FCOS is open daily from 8:00 AM until dusk. There are no fees for parking or for dogs. There are no wheelchair-accessible facilities, no restrooms, no drinking water, no picnic facilities, and no reservable campgrounds.<ref name="EBRPD-5Canyons">[http://www.ebparks.org/parks/five_canyons "Five Canyons Open Space." East Bay Regional Park District.] Accessed August 24, 2017.</ref>
The [[Bay Area Ridge Trail]] connects FCOS to [[Cull Canyon Regional Recreation Area]] to the north and [[Don Castro Regional Recreational Area]] to the west. At some future time, the trail will also connect to [[Garin Regional Park]], [[Dry Creek Regional Park]] and [[Mission Peak Regional Preserve]].<ref name="EBRPD-5Canyons"/>
