A '''waste collection authority''' ('''WCA''') is a [[local authority]] in the [[UK]] charged with the collection of [[municipal waste]]. There are 376 WCAs in [[England]] and [[Wales]] who are responsible for collecting [[waste]] from nearly 22 million homes and some businesses.<ref>[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/subjects/waste/1029679/1029771/?version=1&lang=_e What does a waste collection authority do?]  [[Environment Agency]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217205538/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/subjects/waste/1029679/1029771/?version=1&lang=_e |date=February 17, 2006 }}</ref> The WCA passes on the waste to the [[waste disposal authority]] that is tasked with the ultimate treatment and disposal of that waste. In England WCAs are the [[Districts of England|district councils]] and [[unitary authority|unitary authorities]].

