'''Wood-free paper''' is [[paper]] created exclusively from [[chemical pulp]] rather than [[mechanical pulp]]. Chemical pulp is normally made from  [[pulpwood]], but is not considered [[wood]] as most of the [[lignin]] is removed and separated from the [[cellulose fiber]]s during processing, whereas mechanical pulp retains most of its wood components and can therefore still be described as wood. Wood-free paper is not as susceptible to yellowing as paper containing mechanical pulp.

